ate, five in Katsina State, four in Ogun State, two in Delta State, two in Edo State, one in Kwara State, one in Oyo State, one in the FCT, and one in [[Adamawa State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigerias-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-873|title=UPDATED: 28 dead as Nigeria\u2019s coronavirus cases rise to 873|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=22 April 2020|accessdate=23 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April, there were hundred and eight new cases: seventy eight in Lagos State, fourteen in the FCT, five in Ogun State, four in Gombe State, three in Borno State, two in Akwa Ibom State, one in Kwara State, and one in [[Plateau State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-108-new-coronavirus-cases-total-now-981|title=BREAKING: Nigeria records 108 new COVID-19 cases, total now 981|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=23 April 2020|accessdate=24 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Nigeria medical cases}}hhhhggf\n\n==Reactions==\n===March===\nEarly March, the [[Federal Ministry of Health (Nigeria)|minister of health]] in Nigeria, [[Osagie Ehanire]], announced that 60 persons who had contact with the index Italian patient were under isolation, 40 persons in Ogun State and 20 in Lagos State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisdaylive.com/index.php/2020/03/08/coronavirus-outbreak-round-the-clock-updates|title=Coronavirus Outbreak: Round-the-clock Updates|last=Ifijeh|first=Martins|publisher=[[This Day|This Day Newspaper]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 March, four Chinese citizens were quarantined in Plateau State, they all tested negative the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvcnews.tv/coronavirus-three-chinese-quarantined-in-plateau|title=Coronavirus: Three Chinese quarantined in Plateau|date=1 March 2020|publisher=[[TVC News]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/news/local/coronavirus-chinese-men-test-negative/qzk5jrp|title=Chinese men quarantined in Plateau over coronavirus test negative|last=Famuyiwa|first=Damilare|date=2 March 2020|publisher=Pulse NG|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 March, the governor of Lagos State, [[Babajide Sanwo-Olu]] disclosed that two foreign Nationals from an unnamed Asian country has tested negative to the virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/regional/ssouth-west/379976-coronavirus-two-foreigners-in-nigeria-test-negative.html|title=Coronavirus: Two foreigners in Nigeria test negative|publisher=[[Premium Times]]|last=Adediran|first=Ifeoluwa|date=3 March 2020|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March, the Anambra State government announced that five Chinese citizens tested negative for the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/news/local/coronavirus-anambra-govt-says-5-chinese-citizens-test-negative/wem48xp|title=Coronavirus: Anambra govt says 5 Chinese citizens test negative|date=6 March 2020|publisher=Pulse NG|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref> The Nigeria Centre for Disease Control reported that a total of 219 primary and secondary contacts of the index case had been identified and were being actively monitored.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncdc.gov.ng/themes/common/files/sitreps/02ca174a32597a1e20536b86bed723c7.pdf|title=NCDC Situation Report 6 March 2020 |website=ncdc.gov.ng}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March, the [[President of Nigeria|President]] [[Muhammadu Buhari]] established a Presidential Task Force for the control of the virus in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://guardian.ng/news/buhari-names-task-force-on-coronavirus|last=Daka|first=FTerhemba|title=Buhari names task force on coronavirus|date=10 March 2020|publisher=[[The Guardian (Nigeria)|The Guardian Newspaper]]|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/buhari-sets-up-12-member-task-force-to-control-coronavirus|title=Buhari sets up 12 member Task Force to control Coronavirus|last=Agbakwuru|first=Johnbosco|date=9 March 2020|accessdate=11 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March, [[Turkish Airlines]] cancelled all their flights to Nigeria due to the virus outbreak.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/news/local/coronavirus-turkish-airlines-cancels-flights-to-nigeria-to-curtail-disease-spread/0dx3d3n|title=Turkish Airlines cancels all flights to Nigeria to curtail Coronavirus spread|last=Famuyiwa|first=Damilare|date=10 March 2020|publisher=Pulse NG|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, a woman in Enugu State displayed the symptoms of coronavirus, she tested negative the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecable.ng/enugu-patient-tests-negative-for-coronavirus|title=Enugu patient tests negative for coronavirusdate=16 March 2020|date = 15 March 2020|publisher=[[TheCable]]|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 2020, Nigeria postponed the 20th national sports festival that was supposed to hold in [[Benin City]], Edo State from 22 March to 1 April.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/382312-just-in-nigeria-postpones-national-sports-festival-over-coronavirus.html|title=Nigeria postpones National Sports Festival over coronavirus|publisher=[[Premium Times]]|last=Eludini|first=Tunde|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, the management of the [[National Youth Service Corps]] suspended the 2020 Batch A stream one 21 days orientation exercise indefinitely. The orientation exercise commenced on 10 March and was expected to end on 30 March, before it was suspended after just 8 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecable.ng/breaking-nysc-shuts-orientation-camps-over-coronavirus-fears|title=NYSC shuts orientation camps over coronavirus|last=Awojulugbe|first=Oluseyi|date=18 March 2020|publisher=[[TheCable]]|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> Later the same day, Nigeria placed a travel ban on 13 countries with high cases of the virus, the countries are; [[United States]], [[United Kingdom]], [[South Korea]], [[Switzerland]], [[Germany]], [[France]], [[Italy]], [[China]], [[Spain]], [[Netherlands]], [[Norway]], [[Japan]] and [[Iran]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-fg-places-travel-ban-on-china-italy-us-uk-others|title=UPDATED: FG places travel ban on China, Italy, US, UK, nine others|last=Ogundele|first=Kamarudeen|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> In Katsina State, a Nigerian citizen that returned from [[Malaysia]] displayed the symptoms of the virus, he tested negative the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/just-in-katsina-records-first-suspected-case-of-coronavirus|title=JUST IN: Katsina records first suspected case of coronavirus|last=Danjuma|first=Shehu|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/covid-19-suspected-case-in-katsina-tests-negative|title=COVID-19: Suspected case in Katsina tests negative|last=Danjuma|first=Shehu|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]|date=19 March 2020|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> [[Kano State]] government confirmed that three persons tested negative for the virus in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/covid-19-suspected-cases-tested-negative-in-kano-commissioner|title=COVID-19: Three suspected cases tested negative in Kano \u2014 Commissioner|last1=Bello|first1=Bashir|last2=Murtala|first2=Abdulmumin|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref> Lagos State government banned religious gatherings of over 50 worshippers for 30 days, Ogun State also banned any gathering of more than 50 people for 30 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-lagos-bans-religious-gathering-with-over-50-worshippers|title=UPDATED: Lagos bans religious gathering of over 50 worshippers|last=Ojerinde|first=Dayo|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/coronavirus-ogun-bans-clubs-restaurants-others|title=Coronavirus: Ogun bans night clubs, gatherings over 50|last=Olatunji|first=Daud|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> The [[New Afrika Shrine]] suspended all their programmes indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/afrika-shrine-suspends-activities-over-coronavirus-fears|title=Afrika Shrine suspends activities over Coronavirus fears|last=Akinkuotu|first=Eniola|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Kwara State and Lagos State announced the indefinite closure of their public and private schools, while [[Zamfara State]], Sokoto State, Katsina State, Niger State, Kano State, Jigawa State, [[Kebbi State]] and Kaduna State also closed down their schools for 30 days from 23 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/coronavirus-kwara-shuts-down-schools-indefinitely-from-monday|title=Coronavirus: Kwara shuts down schools indefinitely from Monday|last=Akinyemi|first=Demola|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-coronavirus-lagos-announces-closure-of-schools|title=[BREAKING] Coronavirus: Lagos announces closure of schools|last=Ojerinde|first=Dayo|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://guardian.ng/news/coronavirus-northwest-governors-to-shutdown-schools-for-30-days|last=Alabi|first=Abdulganiyu|title=Coronavirus: NorthWest governors to shutdown schools for 30 days|date=18 March 2020|publisher=[[The Guardian (Nigeria)|The Guardian Newsp