ential medical commodities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/sokoto-closes-inter-state-routes|title=Sokoto closes inter-state routes|last=Olugbemi|first=Adeniyi|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Federal Capital Territory Administration restricted business and commercial activities in the territory to 15 hours daily, starting from 9pm and ending 6am.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://leadership.ng/2020/03/27/covid-19-fcta-restricts-business-activities-to-15-hours|title=COVID-19: FCTA Restricts Business Activities To 15 Hours|last=Aduge-Ani|first=David|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020|publisher=[[Leadership (newspaper)|Leadership Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, Oyo State government placed a dusk to dawn curfew on the state, banning inter-state travel from and into the state, except vehicles carrying food items, medical, pharmaceutical and petroleum products from 29 March, while also reducing the number of people allowed in a social gathering from 30 to 10. The state also announced that all markets will be closed except those selling perishable food items from 29 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/makinde-imposes-curfew-as-oyo-records-new-covid-19-cases|title=Makinde imposes curfew as Oyo records new COVID-19 cases|last=Adeniran|first=Yinka|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=28 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> Osun State government announced the closure of their state borders from 28 March. The state government all announced the closure of their major markets as well as shopping malls, with the exception of pharmaceutical, foods and medical needs outlets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-osun-govt-announces-closure-of-borders|title=COVID-19: Osun govt. announces closure of borders|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=27 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> Katsina State government announced the closure of their state borders from 28 March, allowing only fuel takers and vehicles conveying food items and other essential commodities, but with subject to screening and testing at the point of entry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-katsina-locks-down-borders-restricts-movements|title=COVID-19: Katsina locks down borders, restricts movements|last=Okezie|first=Augustine|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=27 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> Enugu State government announced an indefinite closure of their state borders and inter-state transportation in the state from 31 March, allowing only those on medical emergency services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/breaking-covid-19-enugu-govt-closes-all-borders-markets|title=BREAKING: COVID-19: Enugu govt closes all borders, markets|last=Ogunyinka|first=Victor|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref> Nasarawa State government banned all social and religious gatherings of more than 50 persons, including weddings, churches services and mosque prayers with immediate effect.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/news/local/coronavirus-why-i-went-into-self-isolation-nasarawa-governor/wh05c7k|title=Coronavirus: Why I went into self-isolation - Nasarawa Governor|date=27 March 2020|publisher=Pulse NG|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> The state government also announced the restriction of all movement into the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/nasarawa-enugu-sokoto-katsina-niger-osun-shut-borders|title=Nasarawa, Enugu, Sokoto, Katsina, Niger, Osun shut borders|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=28 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> Niger State government banned the intra and inter-state movement of people and vehicles, exempting only vehicles carrying food items, fuel, medical supplies and other essential services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.von.gov.ng/covid-19-niger-state-government-bans-interstate-movement|title=COVID-19: Niger State Government bans interstate movement|last=Isa|first=Abdul Mohammed|publisher=[[Voice of Nigeria]]|date=27 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> Zamfara State government announced the closure of their state borders with effect from 28 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.plustvafrica.com/coronavirus-zamfara-govt-set-to-shutdown-borders|title=Coronavirus: Zamfara govt. set to shutdown borders|publisher=[[Plus TV Africa]]|date=27 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> Bayelsa State government announced an immediate closure of their sea and land borders into and out of the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/bayelsa-shuts-land-sea-borders|title=COVID-19: Bayelsa shuts land, sea borders|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, Anambra State government announced the closure of their 63 major markets from 31 March, for a period of two weeks, allowing only food items and medicine markets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/breaking-coronavirus-anambra-clloaes-63-markets-for-2-weeks|title=[Breaking] Coronavirus: Anambra clloaes 63 markets for 2 weeks|last=Ujumadu|first=Vincent|date=28 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref> Abia State government announced a four weeks closure of their state borders and markets from 1 April, directing residents to stay at home and allowing only food sellers to operate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.plustvafrica.com/abia-state-locks-down-from-april-1-over-coronavirus|title=Abia State locks down from April 1 over Coronavirus|publisher=[[Plus TV Africa]]|date=28 March 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> Imo State government announced an indefinite ban on all weddings, burial ceremonies and religious activities with immediate effect. The state government also directed all civil and public servants to stop work immediately, except those on approved essential services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/breaking-covid-19-no-more-weddings-burial-in-imo-uzodinma-talks-tough|title=[Breaking] Covid -19: No more weddings, burial in Imo \u2013 Uzodinma talks tough|last=Alozie|first=Chinonso|date=28 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref> Ogun State government announced the closure of their state borders for two weeks in the first instance from 29 March, allowing only vehicles conveying personnel involved in essential services such as security agencies, health workers, food, medical items and petroleum products.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/ogun-closes-borders-over-covid-19|title=Ogun closes borders over COVID \u2013 19|last=Nwokolo|first=Ernest|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=28 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> [[Cross River State]] government banned all religious gatherings of more than five persons in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/covid-19-cross-river-bans-religious-gatherings-of-more-than-5-persons|title=COVID-19: Cross River bans religious gatherings of more than 5 persons|last=Royal|first=David|date=28 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref> Kebbi State government announced the restriction of all entries into and out of the state with immediate effect.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/kebbi-restricts-exit-entry|title=Kebbi restricts exit, entry|last=Saidu|first=Khadijat|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=29 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> [[Taraba State]] government announced the closure of their state borders with effect from 29 March, restricting movement in and out of their state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/taraba-shuts-borders-bans-movement-in-out-over-covid-19|title=Taraba shuts borders, bans movement in, out over COVID-19|last=Bolaji|first=Femi|date=28 March 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, Ekiti State government placed a dusk to dawn curfew on the state, closing the state borders and banning inter-state travel from and into the state for fourteen days, except vehicles carrying food items, medical, petroleum products and other essential goods from 30 March, while also ordering residents to stay at home, except those on essential services. The government also ordered the closure of all businesses, offices and places of worship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/updated-fayemi-imposes-dusk-to-dawn-curfew|title=UPDATED: Fayemi imposes dusk-to-dawn curfew|last=Ibrahim|first=Rasaq|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=29 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> Anambra State government announced the closure of [[River Niger Bridge]] with immediate effect, allowing only vehicles transporting food items and medicines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-anambra-closes-niger-bridge-head|title=COVID -19: Anambra closes Niger Bridge head|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=29 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> Federal government announced the locking down of Lagos State, Ogun State and the FCT, for a period of two weeks from 11pm on 30 March, ordering the citizens of the affected areas to stay in their homes, banning travel to or from other states and announcing the shutdown of businesses and offices, exempting hospitals, food processing, petroleum distribution, banks, power generation and private security companies. The government also exempted workers in telecommunication companies, broadcasters, print and electronic media staff who couldn't work from home.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/updated-buhari-locks-down-lagos-abuja-ogun|title=UPDATED: Buhari locks down Lagos, Abuja, Ogun|last1=Oyeleke|first1=Sodiq|last2=Oyero|first2=Kayode|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/buhari-exempts-banks-others-from-lockdown|title=Buhari exempts banks, others from lockdown|last=Nduka|first=Chiejina|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=30 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> The federal government also suspended the movements of all passenger aircraft all over the country, including commercial and private jets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/buhari-suspends-passenger-planes-operations-over-coronavirus|title=Buhari suspends passenger planes operations over coronavirus|last=Shobiye|first=Hamed|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref> Osun State government announced the total lockdown of their state from 31 March, banning movement of individuals and inter-state movements, allowing only those on essential duties to operate, such as health personnel, fire service, security personnel, environmental officials, power and water supply agencies, media and telecommunication officers. The state also permitted pharmaceutical and medical outfits to open.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvcnews.tv/covid-19-osun-govt-announces-total-lockdown-to-stem-spread-of-pandemic|title=COVID-19: Osun govt announces total lockdown to stem spread of pandemic|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|publisher=[[TVC News]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, Adamawa State government announced the closure of their state borders for fourteen days with effect from 31 March 2020, ordering a total lockdown in the state. The state government also announced that the ban affects tricycle, taxis and bus operators throughout the state. The state government also banned social activities and ordered the closure of all markets, except food markets, medicine markets and filling stations, directing banks to provided skeletal services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/fintiri-orders-adamawa-lockdown-over-coronavirus|title=Fintiri orders Adamawa lockdown over coronavirus|last=Shobiye|first=Hamed|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref> The lockdown of Ogun State that was supposed to start from 30 March, was shifted to commence from 3 April, after the state government made a request to the federal government to allow them provide food for their residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-lockdown-of-ogun-now-shifted-to-friday-says-abiodun|title=BREAKING: Lockdown of Ogun now shifted to Friday- Abiodun|last=Olatunji|first=Daud|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, Bauchi State government announced the closure of their state borders for fourteen days with effect from 2 April, ordering a total lockdown in the state and exempting essential services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/just-in-bauchi-declares-total-lockdown-over-coronavirus|title=JUST IN: Bauchi declares total lockdown over coronavirus|last=Royal|first=David|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref> Kwara State government announced an indefinite closure of their state borders with immediate effect, exempting only vehicles carrying agricultural produce, medical equipments, and officials on essential duties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-kwara-shuts-borders-to-fumigate-markets|title=COVID-19: Kwara shuts borders, to fumigate markets|last=Jimoh|first=Adekunle|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=31 March 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Delta State government reviewed the earlier closure of their state borders and restriction of movement for their residents and announced the exemption of those involved in the transportation of essential supplies such as; food, water, petroleum products, pharmaceutical products and other essential services, noting that banks were to remain open only for skeletal services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/covid-19-okowa-reinforces-lockdown-order-in-delta|title=COVID-19: Okowa reinforces lockdown order in Delta|last=Ahon|first=Festus|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref> Bayelsa State government also reviewed the earlier closure of their state borders with the exemption of vehicles transporting food, drugs and the vehicles conveying personnel on essential duty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-lockdown-gov-diri-relaxes-restrictions|title=COVID-19 lockdown: Gov Diri relaxes restrictions|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=31 March 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> There is concern that with closure of public places in Lagos, many persons might have much difficulty making a living and providing food for themselves and children. There is also concern that if persons return to family farms in the countryside they may unknowingly transmit coronavirus to older relatives.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-52093343 Lagos lockdown over coronavirus: 'How will my children survive?'], BBC, 31 March 2020.</ref>\n\n===April===\nOn 1 April, Taraba State government announced the banning of all public gatherings of more than 20 persons in the state. The state government also ordered the closure of all markets with immediate effect, except those providing essential services such as; pharmacies, food stores and petrol service stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/covid-19-taraba-closes-markets-bans-public-gathering|title=COVID-19: Taraba closes markets, bans public gathering|last=Tyopuusu|first=Justin|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Ondo State government announced the closure of their state borders with effect from 2 April, prohibiting inter-state travels into the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-ondo-declares-three-days-fasting-closes-border|title=COVID-19: Ondo declares three days fasting, closes border|last=Otabor|first=Osagie|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=1 April 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, Bauchi State government reversed the total lockdown in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/bauchi-reverses-curfew-as-borders-remain-close|title=Bauchi reverses curfew as borders remain close|last=Adenuga|first=David|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=2 April 2020|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> Akwa Ibom State government announced an indefinite lockdown of their state, directing residents to stay at home, closing all business premises, markets, shops, motor parks and offices, allowing only grocery shops, pharmacies and those on essential services to operate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/covid-19-gov-emmanuel-announces-total-lockdown-in-akwa-ibom|title=COVID-19: Gov Emmanuel announces total lockdown in Akwa Ibom|last=Odey|first=Patrick|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April, Niger State government relaxed their restriction order with immediate effect, restricting movement from 2 pm to 10pm and allowing movement from 8am to 2pm every day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/updated-niger-relaxes-restriction-order-over-covid-19|title=UPDATED: Niger relaxes restriction order over COVID-19|last=Asishana|first=Justina|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=5 April 2020|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April, Kwara State government announced the total lockdown of their state for 14 days from 10 April, exempting vehicles carrying goods and services. The state government allowed markets selling foods and medications to open on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays, between 10am and 2pm.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/regional/north-central/386941-coronavirus-kwara-govt-imposes-total-shutdown-on-state.html|title=Coronavirus: Kwara govt imposes total shutdown on state|publisher=[[Premium Times]]|date=9 April 2020|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, Anambra State government announced an immediate lockdown of their state for 14 days, directing residents to stay at home and allowing only those on essential services to move around.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/covid-19-anambra-declares-14-day-lockdown|title=COVID-19: Anambra declares 14-day lockdown|last=Okafor|first=Tony|date=11 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Niger State government announced the lockdown of their state from 13 April, exempting those on essential services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/breaking-bello-locks-down-niger-over-covid-19|title=BREAKING: Bello locks down Niger over COVID-19|last=Asishana|first=Justina|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=11 April 2020|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 April, federal government extended the lockdown of Lagos State, Ogun State and the FCT, for another two weeks from 11pm on 13 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/updated-buhari-extends-lockdown-for-two-weeks|title=UPDATED: Buhari extends lockdown for two weeks|last=Ogundele|first=Bolaji|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=13 April 2020|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> Ekiti State extended their state lockdown for another fourteen days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/ekiti-govt-extends-lockdown-by-two-weeks-makes-face-mask-compulsory|title=Ekiti Govt extends lockdown by two weeks, makes face mask compulsory|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=13 April 2020|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April, Delta and Osun States extended their state lockdown for another fourteen days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-delta-extend-lockdown-for-another-14-days|title=COVID-19: Delta extends lockdown for another 14 days|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|last=Edremoda|first=Elo|date=14 April 2020|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/covid-19-oyetola-extends-lockdown-by-14-days|title=COVID-19: Oyetola extends lockdown by 14 days|last=Bamigbola|first=Bola|date=14 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Kano State announced the total lockdown of their state for seven days from 16 April, ordering residents to stay at home, closing all markets, places of worship and public gatherings in state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/updated-ganduje-locks-down-kano-for-one-week|title=UPDATED: Ganduje locks down Kano for one week|last=Adeyemi|first=Kolade|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=14 April 2020|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 April, at least 18 people in Nigeria have been killed by security forces during the enforcement of measures to curb the spread of the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraaf.nl/nieuws/352972282/corona-bloedbad-in-nigeria-politie-schiet-18-mensen-dood|title=Corona-bloedbad in Nigeria: politie schiet 18 mensen dood|date=16 April 2020|website=De Telegraaf |lang=nl}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/nigerian-security-forces-kill-18-curfew-enforcement-200416142503603.html |title=Nigerian security forces kill 18 during curfew enforcement &#124; Nigeria News |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=2020-04-16 |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 April, Nigeria extended the closure of airports to another 2 weeks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/updated-fg-extends-closure-of-airports-by-two-weeks|title=UPDATED: FG extends closure of airports by two weeks|last=Yahaya|first=Faith|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=20 April 2020|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref> Borno State government announced a fourteen days lockdown of their state from 22 April, restricting movement of individuals, banning public gatherings, and allowing providers of essential services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/borno-declares-14-days-lockdown|title=Borno declares 14 days lockdown|last=Duku|first=Joel|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=21 April 2020|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/regional/nnorth-east/388942-coronavirus-borno-declares-14-day-lockdown.html|title=Coronavirus: Borno declares 14-day \u2018lockdown|publisher=[[Premium Times]]|last=Haruna|first=Abdulkareem|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 April, Taraba State government announced a total lockdown of their state from 22 April, restricting movement of individuals and vehicles and allowing workers on essential duties, such as health workers, pharmaceutical shops, fuel stations and media houses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailytrust.com.ng/taraba-govt-announces-total-lockdown-over-covid-19-spread.html|title=Taraba govt announces total lockdown over COVID-19 spread|date=21 April 2020|accessdate=22 April 2020|last=Hunkuyi|first=Magaji Isa|publisher=[[Media Trust|Daily Trust Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April, Kwara State government extended their lockdown for another two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-abdulrazaq-extends-kwara-lockdown|title=COVID-19: AbdulRazaq extends Kwara lockdown|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=23 April 2020|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Coronavirus disease]]s, a group of closely related syndromes\n* [[Li Wenliang]], a doctor at [[Wuhan Central Hospital]] and first to describe the syndrome\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ivory Coast]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Senegal]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa]]\n\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Nigeria|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nigeria| ]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|Nigeria]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Nigeria]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters in Nigeria|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Nigeria]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Nigerian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Nigeria}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nigeria\n| map1            = [[File:States &amp; Territory by confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Nigeria.jpg|States &amp; Territory by confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Nigeria|300px|]]\n| legend1         = Confirmed cases\n| map2            = [[File:Confirmed COVID-19 Deaths in Nigeria.jpg|Confirmed COVID-19 Deaths in Nigeria|300px]]\n| legend2         = Confirmed deaths\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Nigeria]]\n| first_case      = [[Lagos]]\n| arrival_date    = 27 February 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=02|day1=27|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| origin          = [[Milan]], [[Italy]]\n| deaths          = 31\n| recovery_cases  = 197\n| confirmed_cases = 981\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|http://covid19.ncdc.gov.ng}}\n}}\n\nThe first confirmed case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] in [[Nigeria]] was announced on 27 February 2020, when an Italian citizen in [[Lagos]] tested positive for the virus, caused by [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ncdc.gov.ng/news/227/first-case-of-corona-virus-disease-confirmed-in-nigeria|title=FIRST CASE OF CORONA VIRUS DISEASE CONFIRMED IN NIGERIA|date=28 February 2020|publisher=[[Nigeria Centre for Disease Control]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/28/world/africa/nigeria-coronavirus.html|title=Nigeria Responds to First Coronavirus Case in Sub-Saharan Africa|date=28 February 2020|last1=Maclean|first1=Ruth|last2=Dahir|first2=Abdi Latif|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref> On 9 March 2020, a second case of the virus was reported in [[Ewekoro]], [[Ogun State]], a Nigerian citizen who had contact with the Italian citizen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2020/03/09/breaking-nigeria-records-second-case-of-coronavirus|title=Nigeria records second case of Coronavirus|date=9 March 2020|website=[[P.M. News]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nOn 28 January 2020, the [[Federal government of Nigeria]] assured citizens of the country of its readiness to strengthen surveillance at [[List of airports in Nigeria|five international airports]] in the country to prevent the spread of coronavirus. The government announced the airports as [[Enugu State|Enugu]], [[Lagos State|Lagos]], [[Rivers State|Rivers]], [[Kano State|Kano]] and the [[Federal Capital Territory, Nigeria|FCT]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/top-news/374865-coronavirus-nigeria-strengthens-surveillance-at-five-international-airports.html|title=Coronavirus: Nigeria 'strengthens' surveillance at five international airports|publisher=[[Premium Times]]|date=29 January 2020|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Nigeria Centre for Disease Control]] also announced same day that they had already set up coronavirus group and was ready to activate its incident system if any case emerged in Nigeria.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://dailypost.ng/2020/01/28/coronavirus-nigeria-announces-preventive-measures-releases-numbers|title=Coronavirus: Nigeria announces preventive measures, releases numbers|publisher=[[Daily Post (Nigeria)|Daily Post Nigeria]]|last=Odunsi|first=Wale|date=28 January 2020|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2020, following the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|developments of COVID-19 pandemic in mainland China]] and other countries worldwide, the federal government of Nigeria set up a Coronavirus Preparedness Group to mitigate the impact of the virus if it eventually spreads to the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisdaylive.com/index.php/2020/01/31/fg-sets-up-coronavirus-preparedness-group|title=FG Sets up Coronavirus Preparedness Group|last=Ifijeh|first=Martins|publisher=[[This Day|This Day Newspaper]]|date=31 January 2020|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.msn.com/en-xl/africa/nigeria/steps-nigeria-is-taking-to-prepare-for-coronavirus/ar-BBZqjKe|title=Steps Nigeria is taking to prepare for coronavirus|date=29 January 2020|access-date=10 March 2020|website=[[MSN]]}}</ref> On the same day, the [[World Health Organization]] listed Nigeria among other 13 African countries identified as high-risk for the spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisdaylive.com/index.php/2020/02/01/coronavirus-spread-who-lists-nigeria-among-high-risk-countries|title=Coronavirus Spread: WHO Lists Nigeria Among High Risk Countries|last1=Ezigbo|first1=Onyebuchi|last2=Ifijeh|first2=Martins|publisher=[[This Day|This Day Newspaper]]|date=1 February 2020|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 February 2020, a [[Chinese people|Chinese]] citizen presented himself to the [[Government of Lagos State|Lagos State government]] on suspicion of being infected with coronavirus. He was admitted at [[Reddington Hospital]] and was released the following day after testing negative.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://tribuneonlineng.com/breaking-coronavirus-scare-in-lagos-govt-announces-test-result-on-chinese-citizen|title=BREAKING: Coronavirus scare in Lagos, govt announces test result on Chinese citizen|publisher=[[Nigerian Tribune]]|last=Gesinde|first=Seyi|date=27 February 2020|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{align|right|{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Nigeria medical cases chart}}}}\n\n[[File:COVID-19 cases in the Lagos Metropolitan Area.jpg|thumb|COVID-19 cases in The Greater Lagos Metropolitan Area excluding areas falling within Ogun state territory, 18 April|720px]]\n\n===February===\nOn 27 February, Nigeria confirmed its first case in Lagos State, an Italian citizen who works in Nigeria had returned on 25 February from Milan, Italy through the [[Murtala Muhammed International Airport]], fell ill on 26 February and was transferred to Lagos State biosecurity facilities for isolation and testing.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ncdc.gov.ng/news/227/first-case-of-corona-virus-disease-confirmed-in-nigeria |title=Nigeria Centre for Disease Control |website=ncdc.gov.ng |access-date=8 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302150128/https://ncdc.gov.ng/news/227/first-case-of-corona-virus-disease-confirmed-in-nigeria |archive-date=2 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2020/02/28/breaking-deadly-coronavirus-confirmed-in-lagos-nigeria-at-last|title=Breaking: Deadly Coronavirus confirmed in Lagos Nigeria at last|last=Ugbodaga|first=Kazeem|date=28 February 2020|website=[[P.M. News]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March===\nOn 9 March, the second case was confirmed, a Nigerian citizen in [[Ewekoro]], [[Ogun State]] who had contact with the Italian citizen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelstv.com/2020/03/09/breaking-nigeria-confirms-second-case-of-coronavirus|title=Nigeria Confirms Second Case Of Coronavirus|publisher=[[Channels TV]]|date=9 March 2020|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/health/health-news/380886-updated-coronavirus-second-case-confirmed-in-nigeria.html|last=Owoseye|first=Ayodamola|title=UPDATED: Coronavirus: Second case confirmed in Nigeria|publisher=[[Premium Times]]|date=9 March 2020|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/dont-panic-says-govt-as-nigeria-gets-second-coronavirus-case|title=Don't panic, says govt as Nigeria gets second coronavirus case|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=10 March 2020|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, Nigeria confirmed that the second case no longer had the virus in his system and thus tested negative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigerian-who-tested-postive-for-coronavirus-now-negative|title=UPDATED: Nigerian who tested positive for coronavirus now negative|last=Atoyebi|first=Olufemi|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=13 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, Nigeria confirmed the third case in Lagos State, A 30-year-old Nigerian female citizen that returned on 13 March from the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecable.ng/breaking-third-coronavirus-case-confirmed-in-lagos|title=Third coronavirus case confirmed in Nigeria|last=Olatunji|first=Haleem|date=17 March 2020|publisher=[[TheCable]]|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, there were five new cases of the virus: four of the new cases were discovered in Lagos State, while one was discovered in [[Ekiti State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/news/local/coronavirus-nigeria-confirms-5-new-cases/bfderkf|title=Coronavirus: Nigeria confirms 5 new cases|last=Toromade|first=Samson|date=18 March 2020|publisher=Pulse NG|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, there were four new cases of the virus in Lagos State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/breaking-lagos-confirms-four-new-cases-of-covid-19|title=BREAKING: Lagos confirms four new cases of COVID-19|last=Royal|first=David|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]|date=19 March 2020|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://guardian.ng/news/nigerias-coronavirus-cases-rises-to-12-with-four-new-confirmations|last=Erezi|first=Dennis|title=Nigeria's coronavirus cases rises to 12 with four new confirmations|date=19 March 2020|publisher=[[The Guardian (Nigeria)|The Guardian Newspaper]]|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> Nigerian government also announced that the Italian citizen who brought coronavirus to Nigeria has tested negative and was discharged the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-italian-who-brought-coronavirus-to-nigeria-now-negative-lagos|title=Italian who brought coronavirus to Nigeria now negative \u2013 Lagos|last=Ojerinde|first=Dayo|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-italian-who-brought-coronavirus-to-nigeria-discharged|title=UPDATED: Italian who brought coronavirus to Nigeria discharged|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, there were ten new cases: seven in Lagos State, three in the [[Federal Capital Territory, Nigeria|FCT]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/updated-nigeria-records-10-new-positive-cases-of-covid-19|title=UPDATED: Nigeria records 10 new positive cases of COVID-19|last=Emorinken|first=Moses|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=21 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, there were eight new cases: six in Lagos State, one in [[Oyo State]], and one in the FCT.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/coronavirus-nigeria-now-has-26-confirmed-cases-ncdc|title=Coronavirus: Nigeria now has 26 Confirmed cases \u2013 NCDC|last=Alao|first=Abiodun|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=22 March 2020|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/breaking-covid-19-ncdc-confirms-one-new-case-in-fct|title=BREAKING: COVID-19: NCDC confirms one new case in FCT|last=Emorinken|first=Moses|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=22 March 2020|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/coronavirus-ncdc-confirms-30-cases-in-nigeria|title=[BREAKING] Coronavirus: NCDC confirms 30 cases in Nigeria|last=Atoyebi|first=Olufemi|date=22 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, there were ten new cases: six in Lagos State, three in the FCT and one in [[Edo State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://guardian.ng/breakingnews/nigerias-coronavirus-toll-cases-now-40|last=Onyedika-Ugoeze|first=Nkechi|title=Nigeria's coronavirus cases now 40|date=23 March 2020|publisher=[[The Guardian (Nigeria)|The Guardian Newspaper]]|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> They also confirmed their first death, a 67-year-old Suleiman Achimugu, an engineer and former managing director of Pipelines and products Marketing Company, who returned from United Kingdom with underlying health conditions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2020/03/23/achimugu-ex-ppmc-boss-identified-as-nigerias-first-coronavirus-death|title=Achimugu, ex-PPMC boss identified as Nigeria's first coronavirus death|date=23 March 2020|website=[[P.M. News]]|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-updated-first-death-recorded-as-confirmed-cases-rise-to-36|title=COVID-19: UPDATED: First death recorded as confirmed cases rise to 36|last=Emorinken|first=Moses|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, there were four new cases: one in Lagos State, one in Ogun State, one in [[Bauchi State]], and one in the FCT.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-44|title=Nigeria coronavirus cases rise to 44|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, there were seven new cases: three in Lagos State, one in [[Osun State]], one in Rivers State, and two in the FCT.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/updated-coronavirus-cases-hit-51-in-nigeria|title=UPDATED: Coronavirus cases hit 51 in Nigeria|last=Ojerinde|first=Dayo|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, there were fourteen new cases: twelve in Lagos State, one in Bauchi State and one in the FCT.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelstv.com/2020/03/26/breaking-14-new-cases-of-covid-19-confirmed|title=14 New Cases Of COVID-19 Confirmed In Nigeria|publisher=[[Channels TV]]|date=26 March 2020|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> Nigeria announced that they were tracing 4,370 suspected cases of the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/coronavirus-nigeria-tracing-4370-suspected-cases-\u2015-lai-mohammed|title=CORONAVIRUS: Nigeria tracing 4370 suspected cases \u2015 Lai Mohammed|last=Soni|first=Daniel|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, there were sixteen new cases: eight in Lagos State, three in the FCT, two in [[Enugu State]], two in Oyo State, and one in Edo State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-coronavirus-cases-rise-from-65-to-70-in-24-hours|title=BREAKING: Nigeria's COVID-19 cases rise from 65 to 70|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-coronavirus-cases-hit-81-as-ncdc-announces-11-new-cases|title=BREAKING: Nigeria's coronavirus cases hit 81 as NCDC announces 11 new cases|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=28 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> On the same day, Lagos State governor, [[Babajide Sanwo-Olu]] announced that the local governments with the highest number of cases are [[Eti-Osa]] and [[Ikeja]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-ikeja-eti-osa-top-coronavirus-cases-in-lagos|title=Ikeja, Eti-Osa top coronavirus cases in Lagos|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, there were sixteen new cases: seven in Lagos State, four in Oyo State, two in the FCT, one in Osun State, one in [[Kaduna State]], and one in [[Benue State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-eight-new-covid-19-cases-total-now-89|title=UPDATED: Nigeria records eight new COVID-19 cases, total now 89|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=28 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-covid-19-nigerias-cases-hit-97|title=[BREAKING] COVID-19: Nigeria's cases hit 97|last=Oyero|first=Kayode|date=28 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, there were fourteen new cases: nine in Lagos State, and five in the FCT.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-reports-14-new-cases-total-at-111|title=BREAKING: Nigeria reports 14 new cases, total at 111|last=Ojerinde|first=Dayo|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, there were twenty new cases: thirteen in Lagos State, four in the FCT, two in Kaduna State and one in Oyo State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigerias-coronavirus-cases-now-131-as-ncdc-announces-20-new-infections|title=BREAKING: COVID-19 cases rise to 131 in Nigeria|last=Ojerinde|first=Dayo|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Five persons were discharged with one death.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-sanwo-olu-confirms-discharge-of-five-patients|title=COVID-19: Sanwo-Olu confirms discharge of five patients|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=30 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-second-coronavirus-death|title=UPDATED: Nigeria records second coronavirus death|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> The suspected cases that Nigeria were tracing, rose to 6,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-ncdc-to-follow-up-over-6000-contacts-to-curb-spread-of-virus|title=COVID-19: NCDC to follow up over 6000 contacts to curb spread of virus|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=30 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April===\nOn 1 April, Nigeria confirmed thirty five new cases: nine in Osun State, nine in Lagos State, seven in the FCT, five in [[Akwa Ibom State]], two in Edo State, one in Ekiti State, one in Kaduna State, and one in Bauchi State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-12-new-covid-19-cases-total-now-151|title=BREAKING: Nigeria records 12 new COVID-19 cases, total now 151|last=Oyero|first=Kayode|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-23-new-cases-total-now-174|title=BREAKING: Nigeria records 23 new cases of COVID-19, total now 174|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, there were ten new cases: seven in Lagos State, and three in the FCT.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-10-new-cases-in-lagos-abuja|title=BREAKING: Nigeria records 10 new coronavirus cases in Lagos, Abuja|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> They also announced that eleven persons have been discharged.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-coronavirus-11-new-patients-recover-discharged-in-lagos|title=Coronavirus: 11 patients recover, discharged in Lagos|last=Ojerinde|first=Dayo|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, there were twenty five new cases: eleven in Lagos State, six in Osun State, three in the FCT, three in Edo State, one in [[Ondo State]], and one in Oyo State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/breaking-nigeria-records-six-new-cases-of-covid-19|title=BREAKING: Nigeria records six new cases of COVID-19|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> They also announced that five persons have been discharged with two deaths.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/ncdc-apologises-for-error-in-covid-19-results-says-total-now-209|title=NCDC apologises for error in COVID-19 results, says total now 209|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=4 April 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Nigeria announced that they have identified about 6,700 contacts and followed up on about 71 percent, testing about 4,000 people and possessing a total of eight testing labs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-nigeria-gets-additional-labs-tests-4000|title=COVID-19: Nigeria gets additional labs, tests 4,000|last=Emorinken|first=Moses|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, there were five new cases: three in Bauchi State, and two in the FCT.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/breaking-nigeria-records-five-new-covid-19-cases-214-in-total|title=BREAKING: Nigeria records five new COVID-19 cases, 214 in total|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=4 April 2020|access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April, there were eighteen new cases: eleven in Lagos State, four in the FCT, two in Edo State, and one in Kaduna State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-10-new-cases-of-coronavirus-toll-now-224|title=BREAKING: Nigeria records 10 new cases of coronavirus, total now 224|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-eight-new-cases-total-now-232|title=BREAKING: Nigeria records eight new COVID-19 cases, total now 232|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, there were six new cases: two in [[Kwara State]], two in Edo State, one in Rivers State, and one in the FCT.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigerias-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-238|title=UPDATED: Nigeria's coronavirus cases rise to 238|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, there were sixteen new cases: ten in Lagos State, two in the FCT, two in Oyo State, one in [[Delta State]], and one in [[Katsina State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-16-new-covid-19-cases-total-now|title=Nigeria records 16 new COVID-19 cases, total now 254|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, there were twenty two new cases: fifteen in Lagos State, four in the FCT, two in Bauchi State, and one in Edo State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/04/nigeria-records-22-new-cases-of-covid-19-as-total-rise-to-276|title=JUST IN: Nigeria records 22 new cases of COVID-19, as total rises to 276|last=Royal|first=David|date=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April, there were fourteen new cases: thirteen in Lagos State, and one in Delta State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigerias-covid-19-cases-now-288|title=BREAKING: Nigeria records 14 new COVID-19 cases, total now 288|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=9 April 2020|accessdate=9 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 April, there were seventeen new cases: eight in Lagos State, three in Katsina State, two in the FCT, one in [[Niger State]], one in Kaduna State, one in Ondo State, and one in [[Anambra State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigerias-coronavirus-cases-now-305|title=UPDATED: Nigeria's coronavirus cases now 305|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Nigeria announced that they have identified about 8,932 people of interest and monitoring 220.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-we-have-traced-8932-people-of-interest-task-force|title=COVID-19: We have traced 8,932 people of interest \u2013 Task Force|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=10 April 2020|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, there were thirteen new cases: eleven in Lagos State, one in Delta State, and one in [[Kano State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-13-new-cases-total-now-318|title=UPDATED: 10 dead as Nigeria's coronavirus cases rise to 318|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=11 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 April, there were five new cases: two in Lagos State, two in Kwara State, and one in Katsina State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-five-new-coronavirus-cases-total-now-323|title=BREAKING: Nigeria records five new coronavirus cases, total now 323|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=12 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 April, there were twenty new cases: thirteen in Lagos State, two in Edo State, two in Kano State, two in Ogun State, and one in Ondo State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-343-in-nigeria|title=BREAKING: Nigeria records 20 new COVID-19 cases, total now 343|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=13 April 2020|accessdate=13 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Nigeria announced that they have increased testing by 50%, to the current capacity of 1,500 tests per day, testing about 6,000 people and possessing a total of eleven testing labs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/rate-of-covid-19-spread-has-slowed-down-fg|title=Rate of COVID-19 spread has slowed down- FG|last=Ogundele|first=Bolaji|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=13 April 2020|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April, there were thirty new cases: twenty five in Lagos State, two in the FCT, one in Kano State, one in Akwa Ibom State, and one in Edo State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigerias-coronavirus-cases-now-362-after-19-new-infections|title=UPDATED: Nigeria's coronavirus cases now 362 after 19 test positive|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=14 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigerias-coronavirus-cases-now-373-as-lagos-records-11-new-infections|title=UPDATED: Nigeria records 11 new coronavirus cases in Lagos, total now 373|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=14 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Lagos State government announced that their officials visited 118,000 households in two days, identifying 119 persons with the symptoms of the virus in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://saharareporters.com/2020/04/14/after-visiting-118000-households-we-identified-119-persons-covid-19-symptoms-\u2013lagos|title=After Visiting 118,000 Households, We Identified 119 Persons With COVID-19 Symptoms \u2013Lagos Government|date=14 April 2020|publisher=[[Sahara Reporters]]|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April, there were thirty four new cases: eighteen in Lagos State, twelve in Kano State, two in Katsina State, one in Delta State, and one in Niger State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-12-dead-as-nigerias-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-407|title=UPDATED: 12 dead as Nigeria's coronavirus cases rise to 407|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=16 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Nigeria announced that they upgraded to the capacity of testing 3,000 persons per day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-we-now-have-testing-capacity-of-3000-per-day-ncdc|title=COVID-19: We now have testing capacity of 3,000 per day \u2013 NCDC|last=Emorinken|first=Moses|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=15 April 2020|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 April, there were thirty five new cases: nineteen in Lagos State, nine in the FCT, five in Kano State, and two in Oyo State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-35-new-coronavirus-cases-total-now-442|title=UPDATED: Nigeria records 35 new coronavirus cases, total now 442|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=16 April 2020|accessdate=17 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 April, there were fifty one new cases: thirty two in Lagos State, six in Kano State, five in Kwara State, two in the FCT, two in Oyo State, two in Katsina State, one in Ogun State, and one in Ekiti State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-51-new-covid-19-cases-total-now-493|title=BREAKING: 17 dead as Nigeria\u2019s coronavirus cases jump to 493|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=17 April 2020|accessdate=17 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 April, there were forty eight new cases: twenty three in Lagos State, twelve in the FCT, ten in Kano State, two in Ogun State, and one in Oyo State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-19-deaths-as-coronavirus-cases-hit-542|title=BREAKING: Nigeria records 19 deaths as coronavirus cases hit 542|last=Oyero|first=Kayode|date=18 April 2020|accessdate=19 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://guardian.ng/news/ncdc-apologises-to-ekiti-government-over-mistake-on-coronavirus-update |title=NCDC apologises to Ekiti Government over mistake on coronavirus update |date=19 April 2020|publisher=[[The Guardian (Nigeria)|The Guardian Newspaper]]|access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 April, there were eighty six new cases: seventy in Lagos State, seven in the FCT, three in Katsina State, three in Akwa Ibom, one in [[Jigawa State]], one in Bauchi State, and one in [[Borno State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/21-dead-as-coronavirus-spreads-to-21-states-abuja|title=21 dead as coronavirus spreads to 21 states, Abuja|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=20 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 April, there were thirty eight new cases: twenty three in Kano State, five in [[Gombe State]], three in Kaduna State, two in Borno State, two in [[Abia State]], one in the FCT, one in [[Sokoto State]], and one in Ekiti State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigerias-coronavirus-cases-now-665|title=UPDATED: Nigeria records 38 new coronavirus cases, total now 665|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 April, there were hundred and seventeen new cases: fifty nine in Lagos State, twenty nine in the FCT, fourteen in Kano State, six in Borno State, four in Katsina State, three in Ogun State, one in Rivers State, and one in Bauchi State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-117-new-coronavirus-cases-total-now-782|title=UPDATED: Nigeria records 117 new coronavirus cases, total now 782|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=21 April 2020|accessdate=22 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April, there were ninety one new cases: seventy four in Lagos State, five in Katsina State, four in Ogun State, two in Delta State, two in Edo State, one in Kwara State, one in Oyo State, one in the FCT, and one in [[Adamawa State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigerias-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-873|title=UPDATED: 28 dead as Nigeria\u2019s coronavirus cases rise to 873|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=22 April 2020|accessdate=23 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April, there were hundred and eight new cases: seventy eight in Lagos State, fourteen in the FCT, five in Ogun State, four in Gombe State, three in Borno State, two in Akwa Ibom State, one in Kwara State, and one in [[Plateau State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-108-new-coronavirus-cases-total-now-981|title=BREAKING: Nigeria records 108 new COVID-19 cases, total now 981|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=23 April 2020|accessdate=24 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Nigeria medical cases}}\n\n==Reactions==\n===March===\nEarly March, the [[Federal Ministry of Health (Nigeria)|minister of health]] in Nigeria, [[Osagie Ehanire]], announced that 60 persons who had contact with the index Italian patient were under isolation, 40 persons in Ogun State and 20 in Lagos State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisdaylive.com/index.php/2020/03/08/coronavirus-outbreak-round-the-clock-updates|title=Coronavirus Outbreak: Round-the-clock Updates|last=Ifijeh|first=Martins|publisher=[[This Day|This Day Newspaper]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 March, four Chinese citizens were quarantined in Plateau State, they all tested negative the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvcnews.tv/coronavirus-three-chinese-quarantined-in-plateau|title=Coronavirus: Three Chinese quarantined in Plateau|date=1 March 2020|publisher=[[TVC News]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/news/local/coronavirus-chinese-men-test-negative/qzk5jrp|title=Chinese men quarantined in Plateau over coronavirus test negative|last=Famuyiwa|first=Damilare|date=2 March 2020|publisher=Pulse NG|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 March, the governor of Lagos State, [[Babajide Sanwo-Olu]] disclosed that two foreign Nationals from an unnamed Asian country has tested negative to the virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/regional/ssouth-west/379976-coronavirus-two-foreigners-in-nigeria-test-negative.html|title=Coronavirus: Two foreigners in Nigeria test negative|publisher=[[Premium Times]]|last=Adediran|first=Ifeoluwa|date=3 March 2020|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March, the Anambra State government announced that five Chinese citizens tested negative for the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/news/local/coronavirus-anambra-govt-says-5-chinese-citizens-test-negative/wem48xp|title=Coronavirus: Anambra govt says 5 Chinese citizens test negative|date=6 March 2020|publisher=Pulse NG|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref> The Nigeria Centre for Disease Control reported that a total of 219 primary and secondary contacts of the index case had been identified and were being actively monitored.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncdc.gov.ng/themes/common/files/sitreps/02ca174a32597a1e20536b86bed723c7.pdf|title=NCDC Situation Report 6 March 2020 |website=ncdc.gov.ng}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March, the [[President of Nigeria|President]] [[Muhammadu Buhari]] established a Presidential Task Force for the control of the virus in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://guardian.ng/news/buhari-names-task-force-on-coronavirus|last=Daka|first=FTerhemba|title=Buhari names task force on coronavirus|date=10 March 2020|publisher=[[The Guardian (Nigeria)|The Guardian Newspaper]]|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/buhari-sets-up-12-member-task-force-to-control-coronavirus|title=Buhari sets up 12 member Task Force to control Coronavirus|last=Agbakwuru|first=Johnbosco|date=9 March 2020|accessdate=11 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March, [[Turkish Airlines]] cancelled all their flights to Nigeria due to the virus outbreak.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/news/local/coronavirus-turkish-airlines-cancels-flights-to-nigeria-to-curtail-disease-spread/0dx3d3n|title=Turkish Airlines cancels all flights to Nigeria to curtail Coronavirus spread|last=Famuyiwa|first=Damilare|date=10 March 2020|publisher=Pulse NG|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, a woman in Enugu State displayed the symptoms of coronavirus, she tested negative the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecable.ng/enugu-patient-tests-negative-for-coronavirus|title=Enugu patient tests negative for coronavirusdate=16 March 2020|date = 15 March 2020|publisher=[[TheCable]]|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 2020, Nigeria postponed the 20th national sports festival that was supposed to hold in [[Benin City]], Edo State from 22 March to 1 April.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/382312-just-in-nigeria-postpones-national-sports-festival-over-coronavirus.html|title=Nigeria postpones National Sports Festival over coronavirus|publisher=[[Premium Times]]|last=Eludini|first=Tunde|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, the management of the [[National Youth Service Corps]] suspended the 2020 Batch A stream one 21 days orientation exercise indefinitely. The orientation exercise commenced on 10 March and was expected to end on 30 March, before it was suspended after just 8 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecable.ng/breaking-nysc-shuts-orientation-camps-over-coronavirus-fears|title=NYSC shuts orientation camps over coronavirus|last=Awojulugbe|first=Oluseyi|date=18 March 2020|publisher=[[TheCable]]|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> Later the same day, Nigeria placed a travel ban on 13 countries with high cases of the virus, the countries are; [[United States]], [[United Kingdom]], [[South Korea]], [[Switzerland]], [[Germany]], [[France]], [[Italy]], [[China]], [[Spain]], [[Netherlands]], [[Norway]], [[Japan]] and [[Iran]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-fg-places-travel-ban-on-china-italy-us-uk-others|title=UPDATED: FG places travel ban on China, Italy, US, UK, nine others|last=Ogundele|first=Kamarudeen|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> In Katsina State, a Nigerian citizen that returned from [[Malaysia]] displayed the symptoms of the virus, he tested negative the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/just-in-katsina-records-first-suspected-case-of-coronavirus|title=JUST IN: Katsina records first suspected case of coronavirus|last=Danjuma|first=Shehu|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/covid-19-suspected-case-in-katsina-tests-negative|title=COVID-19: Suspected case in Katsina tests negative|last=Danjuma|first=Shehu|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]|date=19 March 2020|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> [[Kano State]] government confirmed that thre